00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:18.839
Load management is certainly the term in the NBA that you've heard publicly. And then the last part,

00:18:18.839 --> 00:18:23.319
last major areas, cap and labor, and that's how you value contracts. There's a lot of different

00:18:23.319 --> 00:18:30.280
ways to value a contract. And again, these are all applications where that expected value framework

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:34.199
can help your organization make positive gains in the long run.

00:18:37.479 --> 00:18:40.199
As I wrap up here, I just want to mention a couple lessons learned

00:18:41.239 --> 00:18:46.359
from this exercise. Really, this is a summary not only from the exercise, the SHINee application,

00:18:47.079 --> 00:18:50.680
but just in general. I'm trying to, when I was putting this presentation together,

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:55.160
I wanted to try to anticipate what some of the questions might be. And hopefully this

00:18:56.439 --> 00:19:00.520
captures some of the potential questions. Again, I'm happy to answer more of these as we get to

00:19:00.520 --> 00:19:05.319
the Q&A section. But the first one is consider framing your decisions as bets. And if you're

00:19:05.319 --> 00:19:10.119
not framing your decisions as bets and you're just looking at it at a deterministic level,

00:19:10.119 --> 00:19:14.119
I would highly encourage you to look at your decision making from a probabilistic mindset.

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:21.319
There, even something that may be perceived as 100%, whether it's a reversal rate, it's a player

00:19:21.319 --> 00:19:27.079
selection, it's a coaching decision, it's a contract decision, I would argue that things

00:19:27.079 --> 00:19:32.439
that are 100%, there is other things can happen and they do happen. So that's why I would highly

00:19:32.439 --> 00:19:37.000
encourage a probabilistic mindset. Another key piece here is a small advantages can equate to

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.800
significant gains in the long run. And hopefully that was illustrated or highlighted in the short

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:46.520
demonstration with the dice rolling. Small advantages, when you do that over multiple,

00:19:47.719 --> 00:19:52.680
over longer time horizons, and you do that at length, those equate to significant gains.

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:56.119
I've already touched on this luck and variance piece. It's real, it happens.

00:19:56.119 --> 00:20:03.400
Things happen in sports, players slip, somebody falls down, everything else could go right on the

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:07.319
play, but somebody slips, it's bad luck, it happens. But on the flip side, the ball can also

00:20:07.319 --> 00:20:12.520
bounce your way. And then the last piece is extremely important. It's valuing the process

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:16.920
and placing a greater emphasis on the process rather than the outcomes. It's a really difficult

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:22.040
thing to do, especially when you're talking about a 16 and now 17 game season for NFL teams.

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:26.760
It's an extremely difficult thing to do because there is such a limited number of games. But if

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:32.359
you value the process and understand that luck is going to happen, but you place an emphasis

00:20:32.359 --> 00:20:37.880
on the process and you can live with when you're making best decisions that are maximizing expected

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:41.640
value, then that's a, in my mind, that's a really good framework for operating.

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:49.560
I'm sure there's a number of people on this call that are attending that maybe are unfamiliar with

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:54.040
sports analytics, want to do something. So here are just some general recommendations on how to

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:57.560
get started. One is first and foremost is go do something. That's a question that whenever I was

00:20:57.560 --> 00:21:02.280
asked by students, one of my first questions would be, what have you done lately? If you're

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:06.439
not familiar with the big data ball, I would highly encourage you to go look at this information.

